-- U.K. FTSE 100 Index Declines as Smith & Nephew, Rio Tinto Falls
-- B y   A l e x i s   X y d i a s
-- 2010-12-29T17:06:46Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-29/ftse-100-stocks-fluctuate-smith-nephew-drops-as-randgold-barrick-climb.html
The U.K.’s benchmark  FTSE 100 Index 
declined, as trading volumes tumbled even as London markets re-
opened following the four-day Christmas break.  Smith & Nephew Plc lost 1.3 percent after U.S. regulators
said the maker of implants violated manufacturing and testing
rules.  Rio Tinto Plc  declined as monsoons in Australia affected
coal production. Randgold Resources Ltd. and African Barrick
Gold Plc rose with metals prices.  The FTSE 100 decreased 12.56, or 0.2 percent, to 5,996.36
at the 4:30 p.m. close in London. A total of 538  million shares 
in FTSE 100 members changed hands today, compared with a daily
average of 1.6 billion this year, according to data compiled by
Bloomberg. The  FTSE All-Share  was little changed at 3,107.41,
while Ireland’s  ISEQ Index  gained 0.4 percent.  The FTSE 100 last week ended above 6,000 for the first time
since June 2008, heading for a 2010 rally of 11 percent and its
best December since 1993. Investors worldwide have poured money
into equities this year as companies reported profits that
exceeded analysts’ estimates and the U.S. Federal Reserve buys
bonds to stimulate economic growth. European benchmark indexes
fell this week after China raised interest rates on Dec. 25.  “We’ve only come back to the Chinese rate move today” in
the U.K. market, said  Will Hedden , sales trader at IG Index in
London. “We are going to still see a pretty quiet week.”  The  Euro Stoxx 50 Index  fell 1.2 percent on Dec. 27 after
China raised rates for the second time in just over two months
to avert inflation in the world’s fastest-growing major economy.  Warning Letter  Smith & Nephew declined 1.3 percent to 677 pence. Europe’s
largest maker of shoulder and knee implants got a warning letter
from the Food and Drug Administration saying the company failed
to properly manufacture, store and test some medical devices.  Rio Tinto  lost 0.5 percent to 4,552.5 pence. The mining
company’s Rio Tinto Coal unit said that as a result of severe
monsoons in central and northern Queensland state, Australia,
force majeure has been declared on coal sales contracts from
mines in which it has a majority interest.  Randgold Resources  rose 3.4 percent to 5,445 pence. African
Barrick climbed 6.3 percent to 618.5 pence, a record advance and
the biggest gain today on the FTSE 100.  Record Gold  Gold rose for the third straight day in New York as
European-debt concerns mounted and the dollar dropped, spurring
demand for a haven. Gold futures reached a record $1,432.50 an
ounce on Dec. 7 amid mounting concern about the fiscal health of
countries including Ireland and Spain. Bullion priced in euros
and British pounds climbed to a all-time highs today.  Hochschild Mining Plc  jumped 3.4 percent to 645 pence. The
London-based miner said it signed a joint venture agreement with
International Minerals Corp. to develop the Inmaculada gold and
silver project in southern Peru.  Anglo American Plc rose 2.1 percent to 3,375.5 pence. The
world’s fifth-largest base-metals producer by market value
agreed to invest as much as 1.3 billion reais ($770 million) in
its iron-ore port project with billionaire Eike Batista’s LLX
Logistica SA to export the mineral from Brazil.  British Airways Plc , the U.K.’s largest airline, fell 0.5
percent to 274.4 pence. As many as 1.2 million airline customers
may have been affected by almost 8,000 flight cancellations
after the snowstorm that hit the U.S. three days ago closed
major airports.  Desire Petroleum Plc  plunged 29 percent to 42.5 pence, the
lowest price since May. The energy explorer said it found no
hydrocarbons in the Jacinta Prospect off the Falkland Islands.  To contact the reporters on this story:
